          </msIdentifier>
          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>The only Gaelic material in the manuscript is Domhnall Gorm's quatrain, now
                lacunose.</p>
            </summary>
            <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS8.1">
              <locus>fol.231v4–6</locus>
              <title>Gaelic Verse Fragment</title>
              <author role="scribe" corresp="Hand21"/>
              <incipit>[...] air cioth na coinne ...</incipit>
              <explicit>... air clar na cruinne</explicit>
              <textLang mainLang="ghc"/>
              <note>
                <p>This single quatrain in <hi rend="italics">rannaigecht beag</hi> is not only
                  lacking in context but is also missing two syllables each from lines a and c. As a
                  result, its interpretation is difficult. The best attempt is a text and
                  translation by William MacKenzie, with the assistance of William Watson (MacKenzie
                  1939: 137). There are no other known manuscript versions of this quatrain, nor any
                  known context from which it might have come </p>
              </note>
